    "id": "mnswhwbk",
    "questionNumber": 38,
    "questionText": "<p>Given below are two statements :</p>\n<p><b>Statement I :</b> Methane can be prepared by decarboxylation of sodium ethanoate, Kolbe's electrolysis of sodium acetate and reaction of $\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{MgBr}$ with water.</p>\n<p><b>Statement II :</b> Methane cannot be prepared from unsaturated hydrocarbons and by Wurtz reaction.</p>\n<p>In the light of the above statements, choose the correct answer from the options given below</p>\n",
    "options": [
      "<p>Both Statement I and Statement II are true</p>\n",
      "<p>Both Statement I and Statement II are false</p>\n",
      "<p>Statement I is true but Statement II is false</p>\n",
      "<p>Statement I is false but Statement II is true</p>"
    ],
    "correctOption": 3,
    "correctAnswer": null,
    "questionType": "MCQ",
    "marks": 4,
    "negativeMarks": -1,
    "subject": "Chemistry",
    "topic": "properties-and-preparation-of-alkanes",
    "difficulty": "medium",
    "solution": "<h3><strong>Analysis of Statement I</strong></h3>\n<p>Statement I says: \"Methane can be prepared by decarboxylation of sodium ethanoate, Kolbe's electrolysis of sodium acetate and reaction of $\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{MgBr}$ with water.\"</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>Decarboxylation of sodium ethanoate:</strong></p>\n<p>This reaction involves heating a sodium salt of a carboxylic acid with soda-lime (a mixture of NaOH and CaO). The general reaction is the removal of a carboxyl group.</p>\n<p>For sodium ethanoate ($CH_3COONa$), the reaction is:</p>\n<p>$$CH_3COONa + NaOH \\xrightarrow{CaO, \\Delta} CH_4 + Na_2CO_3$$</p>\n<p>As you can see, methane ($CH_4$) is indeed the product. So, this part is correct.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Kolbe's electrolysis of sodium acetate:</strong></p>\n<p>Kolbe's electrolytic method involves the electrolysis of an aqueous solution of a sodium or potassium salt of a carboxylic acid.</p>\n<p>For sodium acetate ($CH_3COONa$), at the anode, the acetate ions lose electrons and form methyl free radicals, which then combine to form ethane.</p>\n<p>At Anode:</p>\n<p>$$2CH_3COO^- \\rightarrow 2\\dot{C}H_3 + 2CO_2 + 2e^-$$</p>\n<p>$$\\dot{C}H_3 + \\dot{C}H_3 \\rightarrow CH_3-CH_3 \\text{ (Ethane)}$$</p>\n<p>The product is ethane, not methane. As per our NCERT textbook, this method is used to prepare symmetrical alkanes with an even number of carbon atoms. Methane cannot be prepared by this method.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Reaction of $\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{MgBr}$ with water:</strong></p>\n<p>$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{MgBr}$ is a Grignard reagent (methylmagnesium bromide). Grignard reagents are highly reactive and react with any source of a proton, such as water, to form hydrocarbons.</p>\n<p>The reaction is:</p>\n<p>$$CH_3MgBr + H_2O \\rightarrow CH_4 + Mg(OH)Br$$</p>\n<p>Here, the methyl group from the Grignard reagent takes a hydrogen atom from water to form methane ($CH_4$). So, this part is also correct.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Conclusion for Statement I:</strong></p>\n<p>The statement claims that methane can be prepared by <em>all three</em> methods. Since Kolbe's electrolysis of sodium acetate produces ethane and <strong>not</strong> methane, the entire statement becomes <strong>false</strong>.</p>\n<h3><strong>Analysis of Statement II</strong></h3>\n<p>Statement II says: \"Methane cannot be prepared from unsaturated hydrocarbons and by Wurtz reaction.\"</p>\n<p>Let's check both parts.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>Preparation from unsaturated hydrocarbons:</strong></p>\n<p>Alkanes are prepared from unsaturated hydrocarbons (alkenes and alkynes) by hydrogenation, which is the addition of hydrogen ($H_2$) across the double or triple bond.</p>\n<p>For example:</p>\n<p>$$CH_2=CH_2 \\text{ (Ethene)} + H_2 \\xrightarrow{Ni/Pt/Pd} CH_3-CH_3 \\text{ (Ethane)}$$</p>\n<p>To prepare methane ($CH_4$), which has only one carbon atom, we would need an unsaturated hydrocarbon with one carbon atom. The smallest alkene (ethene) and alkyne (ethyne) have two carbon atoms. A one-carbon alkene or alkyne is not possible. Therefore, methane cannot be prepared by the hydrogenation of unsaturated hydrocarbons. This part is correct.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Preparation by Wurtz reaction:</strong></p>\n<p>The Wurtz reaction involves the treatment of alkyl halides with sodium metal in dry ether to produce higher alkanes. It essentially joins two alkyl groups together.</p>\n<p>The general reaction is:</p>\n<p>$$2R-X + 2Na \\xrightarrow{\\text{dry ether}} R-R + 2NaX$$</p>\n<p>This reaction always results in an alkane with an even number of carbon atoms, and it doubles the carbon chain. To prepare methane ($CH_4$), which has only one carbon atom, we would need to start with an alkyl halide having half a carbon atom, which is impossible.</p>\n<p>If we use the smallest alkyl halide, methyl chloride ($CH_3Cl$), the Wurtz reaction would give ethane:</p>\n<p>$$2CH_3Cl + 2Na \\xrightarrow{\\text{dry ether}} CH_3-CH_3 \\text{ (Ethane)} + 2NaCl$$</p>\n<p>So, methane cannot be prepared by the Wurtz reaction. This part is also correct.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Conclusion for Statement II:</strong></p>\n<p>Both parts of the statement are correct. Methane indeed cannot be prepared from unsaturated hydrocarbons or by the Wurtz reaction. Therefore, Statement II is <strong>true</strong>.</p>\n<h3><strong>Final Decision</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><p>Statement I is <strong>false</strong>.</p></li>\n<li><p>Statement II is <strong>true</strong>.</p></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Looking at the options, this corresponds to the choice where Statement I is false and Statement II is true.</p>\n<p>The correct answer is <strong>Option D</strong>.</p>",
    "section": "A",
    "type": "SCQ"
  },
