  {
    "id": "1l2sqgk7a",
    "questionNumber": 34,
    "questionText": "<p>The maximum number of isomers (including stereoisomers) that are possible on mono-chlorination of the following compound, is ____________.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dheywx/2ec5a646-a273-46b4-893b-e06a21375c16/b38db600-6507-11ef-8452-815a3bbe3903/file-jaoe38c1m0dheyxs.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dheywx/2ec5a646-a273-46b4-893b-e06a21375c16/b38db600-6507-11ef-8452-815a3bbe3903/file-jaoe38c1m0dheyxs.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English\"></p>",
    "options": [],
    "correctOption": 0,
    "correctAnswer": null,
    "questionType": "MCQ",
    "marks": 4,
    "negativeMarks": -1,
    "subject": "Chemistry",
    "topic": "properties-and-preparation-of-alkanes",
    "difficulty": "hard",
    "solution": "<p>(i) The monochlorination products obtained depends upon the kinds of hydrogen present in the molecule.</p>\n<p>(ii) There are four different types of hydrogen in the molecule; $\\mathrm{H}_a, \\mathrm{H}_b, \\mathrm{H}_c$ and $\\mathrm{H}_d$.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dsn44q/ef9cd3b2-39b5-4ed4-bc4e-563a9e0fa0d5/9a75e5d0-6533-11ef-8476-99023ad6136d/file-jaoe38c1m0dsn44t.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dsn44q/ef9cd3b2-39b5-4ed4-bc4e-563a9e0fa0d5/9a75e5d0-6533-11ef-8476-99023ad6136d/file-jaoe38c1m0dsn44t.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 1\"></p>\n<p>(iii) The monochlorination products obtained on replacement of these hydrogen are as follows :</p>\n<p>(a) Replacing $\\mathrm{H}_a$ with chlorine :</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dsqq3e/c3c25250-178a-49f6-8e8e-9d4aaef43aa0/fed9f890-6533-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsqq3f.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dsqq3e/c3c25250-178a-49f6-8e8e-9d4aaef43aa0/fed9f890-6533-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsqq3f.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 2\"></p>\n<p>Since, the carbon is a chiral; only one monochlorination isomer is possible when $\\mathrm{H}_a$ is replaced by chlorine.</p>\n<p>(b) Replacing $\\mathrm{H}_b$ with chlorine :</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dsuc49/ffc22ff5-0bf4-410c-9f12-4e23a16d388e/634adc90-6534-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsuc4a.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dsuc49/ffc22ff5-0bf4-410c-9f12-4e23a16d388e/634adc90-6534-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsuc4a.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 3\"></p>\n<p>Since all the carbons are a chiral; only one monochlorination product is possible by when $\\mathrm{H}_b$ replaced by Cl .</p>\n<p>(c) Replacing $\\mathrm{H}_c$ with chlorine</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dsw3u2/a0c5bbac-7d88-48ea-8023-ee28147e2ee9/94831ca0-6534-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsw3u3.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dsw3u2/a0c5bbac-7d88-48ea-8023-ee28147e2ee9/94831ca0-6534-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsw3u3.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 4\"></p>\n<p>The carbon on which hydrogen is replaced by chlorine becomes chiral; hence R/S isomers exist.</p>\n<p>Also, carbon adjacent to the carbon on which hydrogen $\\left(\\mathrm{H}_c\\right)$ is replaced, is also chiral; hence, it will also exist as a pair of enantiomer $R / S$ four monochlorination products (which are stereoisomers or optical isomers) are possible.\n\n<br><br>(d) Replacing $\\mathrm{H}^d$ by chlorine :</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dt07zc/d3bb8d48-6d1a-4342-b6c9-db2fc6a49452/06f3d590-6535-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dt07zd.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dt07zc/d3bb8d48-6d1a-4342-b6c9-db2fc6a49452/06f3d590-6535-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dt07zd.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 5\"></p>\n<p>The central carbon $\\left({ }^*\\right)$ becomes chiral when $\\mathrm{H}^d$ is replaced by chlorine; hence $R / S$ isomers exist. Two monochlorination products are possible (stereoisomers or optical isomers) are possible. \n<br><br>Total number of isomers possible are 8.</p>",
    "section": "Sec 3",
    "instruction": "",
    "type": "SUBJECTIVE"
  },
  {
    "id": "pe3VuSMjafKGXbUY",
    "questionNumber": 123,
    "questionText": "Which one of the following has the minimum boiling point?",
    "options": [
      "n-butane",
      "isobutane",
      "1- butene ",
      "1- butyne "
    ],
    "correctOption": 1,
    "correctAnswer": null,
    "questionType": "MCQ",
    "marks": 4,
    "negativeMarks": -1,
    "subject": "Chemistry",
    "topic": "properties-and-preparation-of-alkanes",
    "difficulty": "medium",
    "solution": "<b>NOTE :</b> Among isomeric alkanes, the straight chain isomer has higher boiling point than  the branched chain isomer. The greater the branching of the chain, the lower is the boiling point. Further due to the presence of $$\\pi $$ electrons, these molecules are slightly polar and hence have higher boiling points than the corresponding alkanes. \n<br><br>Thus $$B.pt.$$ follows the order\n<br><br>alkynes $$&gt;$$ alkene $$&gt;$$  alkanes (straight chain) &gt; branched chain alkanes. ",
    "section": "A",
    "type": "SCQ"
  }
]